## Limits and escalation

| Setting | Value | Overridable |
|---|---|---|
| Max iterations (whole run) | {{MAX_ITERATIONS}} | yes |
| Consecutive-FAIL escalation threshold | {{FAIL_THRESHOLD}} | yes |
| Work branch | `{{WORK_BRANCH}}` | yes |
| Commit on PASS | {{COMMIT_ON_PASS}} | yes |

On reaching either limit the loop **stops and escalates to a human** via `LOOP_ESCALATION.md`.
It never continues past the ceiling and never merges on its own.

## Checkpoints

Each passed unit commits to `{{WORK_BRANCH}}` — small, one goal, reviewable, with a message
capturing what changed and why. These commits are the rollback points and the audit trail.

## Stopping conditions

The loop ends when: the queue is empty / the single task PASSes, the max-iteration ceiling is
hit, or a unit escalates after the FAIL threshold.

## Safety (overridable, but defaults are deliberate)

- **Never auto-merge** to the default branch. Work stays on `{{WORK_BRANCH}}`; a human opens
  and merges the PR.
- **Prefer reversible actions.** Deletes, deploys, and migrations are gated on explicit human
  approval, not performed by the loop.
- **Least privilege.** The loop gets only the tools and paths it needs.
- **Sandbox before loosening permissions.** Only relax permissions inside a container without
  network access.

## Comprehension-debt guard

Every checkpoint includes a plain-language summary of what changed and why, so a human can
understand merged code rather than inherit a black box. The verifier confirms this exists
before PASS.

